======================================================================
AUTO-GENERATED INTERPRETATION PARAGRAPHS
======================================================================

Configuration 1 (varying n_components, alpha=0.5 fixed):
The 53-component SparsePCA model achieved the highest classification accuracy
with a mean effect size of 0.324 and bootstrap stability of 0.854.
Relative to other component settings, this configuration captures the most discriminative
and stable spectral structure while avoiding weaker or noisier sparse components that
appear in larger latent spaces.


Configuration 2 (varying alpha, n=32 fixed):
Alpha=0.5 produced the strongest balance of discriminative power (mean η²=0.357)
and stability (0.861). Lower alpha values yield denser components with higher
inter-component redundancy, while higher alpha values over-regularize, stripping chemically
relevant information from the latent space.


Component-level interpretation (n=32, alpha=0.5):
Of the 32 sparse components, 32 showed statistically significant class separation
after Benjamini-Hochberg correction (q < 0.05). SC1 exhibited the strongest
discriminative power (η² = 0.809, H = 288.06),
driven primarily by spectral markers around 1641, 1707, 1637, 1598, 1602 cm⁻¹, consistent with Amide I / C=O stretch (proteins).
SC22 showed the strongest monotonic association with ordered maturity progression
(Spearman ρ = -0.504), with dominant loadings at 3817, 3825, 3813, 3821, 3809 cm⁻¹.
Bootstrap stability of SC1 was 0.982, confirming that this component
captures stable, reproducible spectral structure across resampled fits.